00:00:47.980 --> 00:00:51.990
I write for "Time" magazine.

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:55.570
The only beat I cover is myself
because it's the only

00:00:55.570 --> 00:00:56.750
thing I'm interested in.

00:00:56.750 --> 00:00:58.490
And no one was covering
that beat.

00:00:58.490 --> 00:01:03.130
I got there in 1997.

00:01:03.130 --> 00:01:05.300
I was writing for a magazine
called "Time Out New York,"

00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:09.640
and this editor at "Time" asked
me to write a piece for

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:12.580
this quarterly they did called
"Time Digital," back when

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:14.480
people-- like the internet
was new and people were

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:15.470
excited about it.

00:01:15.470 --> 00:01:17.990
You had a lot more magazines
like "Red Herring" and

00:01:17.990 --> 00:01:18.880
"Business 2.0."

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:24.510
And so I went to Kansas City and
Minneapolis, to find the

00:01:24.510 --> 00:01:27.490
world's greatest video
game player.

00:01:27.490 --> 00:01:29.580
And I'd never been on a
business trip before.

00:01:29.580 --> 00:01:32.350
I was like barely old enough to
rent a car, which they make

00:01:32.350 --> 00:01:35.300
impossible until you're like
30 for some reason.

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:39.960
And I remember sitting in my
hotel room having to write it

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:40.520
that night.

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:43.890
It was due the next day, and
just freaking out, like

00:01:43.890 --> 00:01:46.560
writing for anything that
"Time" magazine put

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:47.720
out seemed so scary.

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:49.020
And I was just panicked.

00:01:49.020 --> 00:01:49.790
And I couldn't write.

00:01:49.790 --> 00:01:53.370
And I drove around Minneapolis
for a while.

00:01:53.370 --> 00:01:55.915
I got to a Steak 'n Shake.

00:01:55.915 --> 00:01:56.730
I drove in.

00:01:56.730 --> 00:01:59.920
I was just going to get an ice
tea or something, and I went

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:01.680
up to the drive-through box.

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:03.130
And the woman said,
can I help you?

00:02:03.130 --> 00:02:09.030
And I said, yeah, I just
really want to talk.

00:02:09.030 --> 00:02:10.169
And she said, OK.

00:02:10.169 --> 00:02:12.010
And so I told her my problems.

00:02:12.010 --> 00:02:12.920
I had this story to write.

00:02:12.920 --> 00:02:14.430
It's for "Time" magazine.

00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:17.970
I keep picturing 4 million
people reading it.

00:02:17.970 --> 00:02:19.870
And she gave me the most amazing
pep talk, which was

00:02:19.870 --> 00:02:21.470
like, they wouldn't have hired
you if they didn't think you

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:22.740
could do it.

00:02:22.740 --> 00:02:24.300
You've done this before.

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:25.530
Don't get in your
head so much.

00:02:25.530 --> 00:02:27.790
And it was so incredibly
helpful.

00:02:27.790 --> 00:02:30.690
And I drove up and I--

00:02:30.690 --> 00:02:33.330
we didn't have the connection
I kind of hoped we'd have.

00:02:33.330 --> 00:02:34.770
It's one thing when
you're talking to

00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:35.560
someone through a box.

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:35.970
And then you see--

00:02:35.970 --> 00:02:37.310
I thought she'd be
my future wife.

00:02:37.310 --> 00:02:39.190
And it didn't work out.

00:02:39.190 --> 00:02:40.450
But I did go home
and I wrote it.

00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:43.070
I went to the hotel
and I wrote it.

00:02:43.070 --> 00:02:44.870
A couple months later, I got
hired by "Time" magazine,

00:02:44.870 --> 00:02:46.240
which freaked me out.

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:50.800
Because I thought I'd have to
write super boring stuff for

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:51.530
the rest of my life.

00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:55.090
But they were paying me in real
money instead of in food,

00:02:55.090 --> 00:02:57.660
which is what I was getting paid
at "Time Out New York."

00:02:57.660 --> 00:02:58.900
Which I think you get paid--

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:01.610
do they pay you in food or they
also you a salary here?

00:03:01.610 --> 00:03:03.792
Because I would do it
just for the food.

00:03:03.792 --> 00:03:05.245
But that's why I'm
a journalist and

00:03:05.245 --> 00:03:07.955
you guys are engineers.

00:03:07.955 --> 00:03:10.360
So I've been working at
"Time" since '97.

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:14.310
And what I've found is that the
best way for me to learn

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:16.610
things is by doing things.

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:21.920
So when I write about something,
even if it doesn't

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:25.210
go in the article, even if the
article's all in third person,

00:03:25.210 --> 00:03:27.100
I usually go do something
to understand it.

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:32.430
Like I recently wrote a profile
of Steve Ells, the CEO

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:33.490
of Chipotle.

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:35.460
And I kind of thought
I got him.

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:36.840
I thought I got the company.

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:39.090
But then they got the company
to let me work at a Chipotle

00:03:39.090 --> 00:03:40.670
for half a day.

00:03:40.670 --> 00:03:43.440
And then I kind of really got
what they were telling me.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.690
It's really hard for me,
although I did fine in school,

00:03:46.690 --> 00:03:48.170
to learn any other way.

00:03:48.170 --> 00:03:52.190
So that's kind of how I got
to writing this book.

00:03:52.190 --> 00:03:54.850
And kind of how I do most of my
stories in "Time." I had to

00:03:54.850 --> 00:03:58.140
do a cover on George Clooney.

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:00.400
And I didn't know-- like
sitting down with

00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:01.580
him seemed so boring.

00:04:01.580 --> 00:04:05.950
So I invited him over my house
for dinner thinking he would

00:04:05.950 --> 00:04:08.060
say no, but just so it would buy
me time to think of more

00:04:08.060 --> 00:04:09.090
interesting things.

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:11.420
And he said yes.

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:13.130
At which point, I had to tell
my wife that George Clooney

00:04:13.130 --> 00:04:17.430
was coming over for dinner,
which if anyone has a normal

00:04:17.430 --> 00:04:18.649
wife and a normal
relationship--

00:04:18.649 --> 00:04:19.950
I forgot this is on YouTube.

00:04:19.950 --> 00:04:23.680
If anyone has a wife who

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:25.120
occasionally Googles her husband--

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:25.940
my wife doesn't care.

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:27.270
This is fine.

00:04:27.270 --> 00:04:29.110
Yeah, she was pissed.

00:04:29.110 --> 00:04:31.390
She was like, I have
to clean the house

00:04:31.390 --> 00:04:33.840
and make like a playlist.

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:35.420
Like you're cleaning it and
you're making dinner.

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:36.530
I'm like, yeah, of course.

00:04:36.530 --> 00:04:42.980
So she got drunk and so
did George Clooney.

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:46.280
And she spent a half hour just
grilling him on why he doesn't

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:50.210
have a wife, which I was
so happy about, just

00:04:50.210 --> 00:04:51.640
taking crazy notes.

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:53.930
And didn't make it in
the piece, my editor

00:04:53.930 --> 00:04:54.480
kept cutting it.

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:58.140
I kept putting it back in and
my editor kept cutting it.

00:04:58.140 --> 00:05:01.130
But yeah, so there is video.

00:05:01.130 --> 00:05:05.900
I find that the things I do,
because some of them--

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:07.920
I think because journalists
lie all the time, people

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:10.020
assume that I'm lying.

00:05:10.020 --> 00:05:12.750
So I've taken to, if I
ever can remember.

00:05:12.750 --> 00:05:15.810
And it's easier now when I have
my Google Android phone

00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:18.430
in my pocket.

00:05:18.430 --> 00:05:20.430
I shoot video whenever I can.

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:25.550
Like when Clooney was over, this
alarm started going off.

00:05:25.550 --> 00:05:27.980
I just figured I'd ignore it
because that's what I do when

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:29.060
alarms go off.

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:31.380
And he had been a handy man.

00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:33.110
He's like, no, we're
going to fix this.

00:05:33.110 --> 00:05:35.710
Let's figure out where this
alarm's coming from.

00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:38.180
So he wound up looking
all over my house.

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:42.600
He went under my house
and got this ladder,

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:43.320
way under my house--

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:43.910
I live in the Hills.

00:05:43.910 --> 00:05:46.880
And then he brought it and went
into my attic, which I

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:49.160
now call the Clooney
attic, because I've

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:50.540
never been in there.

00:05:50.540 --> 00:05:52.080
I still haven't been in there.

00:05:52.080 --> 00:05:54.270
And he went up there
with a flashlight,

00:05:54.270 --> 00:05:55.330
a little bit drunk.

00:05:55.330 --> 00:05:57.160
And so I videotaped
all of this.

00:05:57.160 --> 00:06:01.810
It turned out under our table
was a monoxide alarm.

00:06:01.810 --> 00:06:04.450
It just needed a new battery,
which we figured out

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:05.710
eventually.

00:06:05.710 --> 00:06:07.030
We would have got there
much earlier if

00:06:07.030 --> 00:06:07.700
we hadn't been drinking.

00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:10.330
But I videotaped it.

00:06:10.330 --> 00:06:13.000
And now people who read this
story don't think believed he

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.520
was in my attic, but
you see the video.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:17.320
So for the book, I tried to
videotape as much of me

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:21.210
getting beat up as I could, so
that people would believe it.

00:06:21.210 --> 00:06:25.510
So for the book, I found out--

00:06:25.510 --> 00:06:26.880
my wife was pregnant.

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:29.460
And we were going to the first
sonogram where we could

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:31.540
probably tell if it was
a boy or a girl.

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:35.090
And I remember thinking
that I don't care if

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:37.037
it's a boy or girl.

00:06:37.037 --> 00:06:40.090
I'm a child of the '70s.

00:06:40.090 --> 00:06:43.990
I understand both genders
are lovely.

00:06:43.990 --> 00:06:46.060
I've enjoyed both-- that's
weird to say.

00:06:49.510 --> 00:06:50.380
Totally straight.

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:52.980
I couldn't be more straight.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:54.250
Do I find some men attractive?

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:56.440
Sure, we all do.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:00.590
But I've never gone to second
base with a guy, ever.

00:07:00.590 --> 00:07:01.560
Leave it there.

00:07:01.560 --> 00:07:04.560
So I thought I didn't care.

00:07:04.560 --> 00:07:09.760
Went to get the sonogram
and they told us that

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:11.360
our son was a boy.

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:17.640
In fact, our OB/GYN who I will
not name is amazing, super

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:20.630
cool, super smart women,
went to Princeton.

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:24.960
Just super smart.

00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:27.145
But when she gave us the--

00:07:27.145 --> 00:07:30.230
when you go to a sonogram now,
you get the equivalent of like

00:07:30.230 --> 00:07:34.000
a photo booth strip of pictures
of your child.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:40.030
And she said to us,
it's a boy.

00:07:40.030 --> 00:07:41.690
Wow, he's got a really
big penis.

00:07:44.350 --> 00:07:46.620
If things don't work out for him
in school, he can always

00:07:46.620 --> 00:07:48.360
work in the Valley.

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:50.710
And like, this is
all so weird.

00:07:50.710 --> 00:07:52.230
I'm just processing
information.

00:07:52.230 --> 00:07:53.580
She gives us this photo strip.

00:07:53.580 --> 00:07:57.270
She draws like a penis and
testicles and writes, wow,

00:07:57.270 --> 00:07:59.440
exclamation point next to it.

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:06.610
And all I'm thinking is, we need
a new OB/GYN for sure.

00:08:06.610 --> 00:08:09.600
But I'm also having like a
mini-panic attack where I'm

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:11.170
freaking out because
I'm picturing--

00:08:11.170 --> 00:08:12.460
all I can picture
is that penis.

00:08:12.460 --> 00:08:16.300
And that penis wanting
to throw a baseball.

00:08:16.300 --> 00:08:18.310
And that penis wanting
to go camping.

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:19.940
And that penis getting
in a fight, needing

00:08:19.940 --> 00:08:20.980
to know how to fight.

00:08:20.980 --> 00:08:23.415
And I like, I'm not capable
of any of that stuff.

00:08:23.415 --> 00:08:26.870
When I was a kid, all my
friends were girls.

00:08:26.870 --> 00:08:30.800
I listened to nothing but show
tunes until I was like 13.

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:33.504
I had a glass animal
collection.

00:08:33.504 --> 00:08:38.120
I had an Easy Bake Oven, which
I still think is awesome

00:08:38.120 --> 00:08:41.429
because you can make
cakes in your room.

00:08:41.429 --> 00:08:44.460
But a lot of other
boys didn't.

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:45.590
I never went camping.

00:08:45.590 --> 00:08:47.030
I never played Little League.

00:08:47.030 --> 00:08:48.960
I just thought, my son's going
to want to do all this stuff

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:50.540
and I'm not going
to be able to.

00:08:50.540 --> 00:08:53.130
So I went out and tried to learn
all the things I should

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:56.500
have learned long before this.

00:08:56.500 --> 00:08:59.630
I went on a series of what
I call manventures.

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:03.210
And the first thing I did was
I figured I'd fix the first

00:09:03.210 --> 00:09:05.220
problem, which was not
becoming a Boy Scout.

00:09:05.220 --> 00:09:08.840
So I called the Boy Scouts and
they said I could, indeed,

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:09.870
earn my first badge.

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:13.620
And so I went on a camping
trip for a weekend with

00:09:13.620 --> 00:09:15.100
11-year-old Boy Scouts.

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:18.520
And put up my first tent
and slept in it.

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:22.390
I learned the difference between
sleeping in a tent and

00:09:22.390 --> 00:09:25.920
sleeping just not in a
tent doesn't exist.

00:09:25.920 --> 00:09:28.640
I don't know who the tent
industry has fooled.

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:31.480
But it's still cold.

00:09:31.480 --> 00:09:34.040
It's wet when you lay.

00:09:34.040 --> 00:09:37.190
I either had the wrong tent or
everyone else is an idiot.

00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:41.600
So I went on a bunch of
these adventures.

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:41.900
Let's see.

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:44.130
I did so many things that I've
blocked out of my head because

00:09:44.130 --> 00:09:44.840
they are painful.

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:48.810
I got a day trader to give me
$100,000 to day trade with of

00:09:48.810 --> 00:09:50.800
his money for a day
in Chicago.

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:55.792
I worked in a pit crew of a
racing team, the America Le

00:09:55.792 --> 00:09:56.600
Mans racing.

00:09:56.600 --> 00:10:01.130
Team I had a Lamborghini
Superleggera for 3 days, which

00:10:01.130 --> 00:10:02.860
was incredibly fun.

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:07.450
I helped my very manly
father-in-law fix a house,

00:10:07.450 --> 00:10:09.452
re-roof and do some
plumbing work in a

00:10:09.452 --> 00:10:12.020
house for three days.

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:13.680
I went turkey hunting.

00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:16.160
Have any of you ever gone
turkey hunting?

00:10:16.160 --> 00:10:16.770
I'm at Google.

00:10:16.770 --> 00:10:18.900
I'm asking silly questions.

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:21.590
Have any of you ever played a
video game in which turkey

00:10:21.590 --> 00:10:23.420
hunting takes place?

00:10:23.420 --> 00:10:23.940
AUDIENCE: "Duck Hunt."

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:25.225
JOEL STEIN: "Duck Hunt."
That's close.

00:10:25.225 --> 00:10:27.220
I, too, have played "Duck
Hunt." Turkey hunting is

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:29.750
totally different than
"Duck Hunt."

00:10:29.750 --> 00:10:31.770
So I had this crush on a girl
from kindergarten to fifth

00:10:31.770 --> 00:10:34.820
grade named Bizzy Sklars.

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:35.870
Very worthwhile crush.

00:10:35.870 --> 00:10:38.520
And In fact, nothing to
do with this story,

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:40.130
just want to brag--

00:10:40.130 --> 00:10:43.030
after college, kissed
her at a bar.

00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:45.250
A bar called The
Village Idiot.

00:10:45.250 --> 00:10:47.100
Only time I've ever kissed
a woman at a bar.

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:47.600
Village Idiot.

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:48.340
It closed now.

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:49.860
Yeah, I think it was owned by
the same people that own

00:10:49.860 --> 00:10:52.860
Coyote Ugly, perhaps.

00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:53.300
Yeah.

00:10:53.300 --> 00:10:56.490
But anyway, I kissed
Bizzy Sklars there.

00:10:56.490 --> 00:10:57.150
Wrote it on the wall.

00:10:57.150 --> 00:10:59.330
Didn't write it on the wall,
wrote it in my book.

00:10:59.330 --> 00:11:04.410
And so Bizzy did not
want to marry me.

00:11:04.410 --> 00:11:10.360
She wound up marrying a very
