I'm not good at sports.

00:33:53.830 --> 00:33:58.420
There were very few options
for me to get attention.

00:33:58.420 --> 00:34:00.700
And I think I developed
a sense of humor.

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:02.200
First of all, I'm Jewish.

00:34:02.200 --> 00:34:06.810
And so that's kind of the
mode of communication.

00:34:06.810 --> 00:34:09.840
And my parents think they're
funny and don't use YouTube,

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:11.090
so I can say that.

00:34:13.280 --> 00:34:16.080
And I just was impressed
by the--

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:19.810
there was a punkishness to
comedy that really appealed to

00:34:19.810 --> 00:34:21.510
me, because it wasn't the angry

00:34:21.510 --> 00:34:23.469
punkishness of punk rock.

00:34:23.469 --> 00:34:30.330
But it was kind of an inside,
self-aware kind of flipping

00:34:30.330 --> 00:34:30.720
off the man.

00:34:30.720 --> 00:34:32.010
And that really appealed
to me.

00:34:32.010 --> 00:34:33.840
So I was obsessed
about Letterman.

00:34:33.840 --> 00:34:36.010
I subscribed to "Spy"
magazine.

00:34:36.010 --> 00:34:38.429
Letterman read one of my
questions on air when I was in

00:34:38.429 --> 00:34:40.420
high school, which
is the highlight

00:34:40.420 --> 00:34:43.110
of my writing career.

00:34:43.110 --> 00:34:45.080
I tried like seven times till
I figured out how to get a

00:34:45.080 --> 00:34:47.969
letter on Letterman.

00:34:47.969 --> 00:34:49.590
So I didn't really think
of it as a career.

00:34:49.590 --> 00:34:51.969
I thought I'd be a lawyer
because that's all I could

00:34:51.969 --> 00:34:54.594
think of what people who
don't have skills do.

00:34:54.594 --> 00:34:56.820
And so I wrote for my
high school paper.

00:34:56.820 --> 00:34:57.600
I wrote a column.

00:34:57.600 --> 00:34:59.960
I wrote a column for my college
paper that was far

00:34:59.960 --> 00:35:01.670
more popular than my
column is now.

00:35:01.670 --> 00:35:04.700
And I interned at "Newsweek"
because some professor at

00:35:04.700 --> 00:35:06.920
Stanford who read my stuff in
the school paper got me an

00:35:06.920 --> 00:35:08.130
internship there.

00:35:08.130 --> 00:35:11.210
And then it started to
look more feasible.

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:14.390
I gave myself two years before
law school out of college.

00:35:14.390 --> 00:35:18.080
And when those two years ended
and I still fact checking and

00:35:18.080 --> 00:35:20.830
not writing, I decided to give
myself another two years.

00:35:20.830 --> 00:35:24.250
And I was going to move to LA
and try sitcom writing.

00:35:24.250 --> 00:35:25.160
That was my next two years.

00:35:25.160 --> 00:35:26.480
I'm sure I would have found
out another two

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:27.900
years until I died.

00:35:27.900 --> 00:35:31.410
And eventually, becoming some
kind of a sonnet writer.

00:35:31.410 --> 00:35:32.970
But instead, this new
magazine, "Time

00:35:32.970 --> 00:35:34.380
Out New York," started.

00:35:34.380 --> 00:35:37.350
And a guy I knew from working
at Martha Stewart got a job

00:35:37.350 --> 00:35:41.770
there and got me an interview.

00:35:41.770 --> 00:35:43.160
It was only two years.

00:35:43.160 --> 00:35:46.220
And to struggle for two years in
today's economy, or even in

00:35:46.220 --> 00:35:47.390
the early '90s is amazing.

00:35:47.390 --> 00:35:48.590
But if you don't know
it's two years, it

00:35:48.590 --> 00:35:50.990
seems kind of endless.

00:35:50.990 --> 00:35:51.570
It was hard.

00:35:51.570 --> 00:35:54.560
It was hard-- and I started
not as a humor writer.

00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:55.470
I started as a journalist.

00:35:55.470 --> 00:35:58.080
And I tried to keep getting
people to run my column.

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:00.180
And I got "Time Out"
to run it.

00:36:00.180 --> 00:36:01.590
And then when I got to "Time,"
I kept running

00:36:01.590 --> 00:36:03.000
the "Time Out" column.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.810
And then eventually, the editor
of "Time--" I thought

00:36:05.810 --> 00:36:07.320
the world was much
smaller than--

00:36:07.320 --> 00:36:09.500
even before the internet, it was
even easier to believe the

00:36:09.500 --> 00:36:10.570
world was tiny.

00:36:10.570 --> 00:36:12.510
So I believed that the old
people who worked at "Time"

00:36:12.510 --> 00:36:15.370
would never see my column at
"Time Out New York," which was

00:36:15.370 --> 00:36:16.290
incredibly stupid.

00:36:16.290 --> 00:36:17.740
And of course, they did.

00:36:17.740 --> 00:36:19.470
And I didn't get in trouble.

00:36:19.470 --> 00:36:22.910
And instead Walter Isaacson, who
was my boss offered to run

00:36:22.910 --> 00:36:23.810
my column in "Time."

00:36:23.810 --> 00:36:27.760
And I just remember like, one
of those moments where your

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:30.230
adrenaline gets going and you
see the world kind of like

00:36:30.230 --> 00:36:31.730
sharpens and shrinks.

00:36:31.730 --> 00:36:34.120
And I remember just like,
this is crazy.

00:36:34.120 --> 00:36:36.870
So I've basically been writing
a column since 1997 for

00:36:36.870 --> 00:36:42.500
"Time." People think I would get
bored of it, but instead

00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:43.480
the readers get bored.

00:36:43.480 --> 00:36:47.190
But I keep having to find new
readers who don't get bored.

00:36:47.190 --> 00:36:50.200
So I still really like it.

00:36:50.200 --> 00:36:51.352
I don't think I answered any of
your questions, but I got

00:36:51.352 --> 00:36:53.260
to talk about me.

00:36:53.260 --> 00:36:56.430
I had a good time.

00:36:56.430 --> 00:36:58.570
AUDIENCE: Through all the
manventures you've gone on,

00:36:58.570 --> 00:37:03.220
have any of them kind
of stuck as hobbies?

00:37:03.220 --> 00:37:04.520
JOEL STEIN: Hobbies, no.

00:37:04.520 --> 00:37:07.550
And all men have hobbies, but
I don't have any hobbies.

00:37:07.550 --> 00:37:10.750
I remember sitting down at the
cafeteria at Fort Knox, which

00:37:10.750 --> 00:37:13.280
is where "Stripes" was
shot and I did my

00:37:13.280 --> 00:37:16.820
fainting with the Army.

00:37:16.820 --> 00:37:18.580
What I also learned from writing
this book is that I

00:37:18.580 --> 00:37:20.270
can now talk to guys
in the military.

00:37:20.270 --> 00:37:21.770
If I see a guy at
the airport--

00:37:21.770 --> 00:37:23.890
if i saw a guy in uniform
at the airport, I never

00:37:23.890 --> 00:37:24.810
knew what to do.

00:37:24.810 --> 00:37:27.900
I didn't know like,
do you thank him?

00:37:27.900 --> 00:37:29.950
Or that just annoys them?

00:37:29.950 --> 00:37:31.790
Or do you like, offer them your
seat or is that treating

00:37:31.790 --> 00:37:33.060
them like an old person?

00:37:33.060 --> 00:37:34.480
I never knew how to deal.

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:36.480
And now I just talk to them
about where they did boot

00:37:36.480 --> 00:37:39.080
camp, and talk about
boot camp stuff.

00:37:39.080 --> 00:37:41.330
The Army let me fire a tank.

00:37:41.330 --> 00:37:44.220
So I'm the first civilian to
ever fire a tank and the last

00:37:44.220 --> 00:37:45.770
civilian who will ever
fire a tank.

00:37:45.770 --> 00:37:47.495
So I can talk to the,
about tanks now.

00:37:53.217 --> 00:37:55.460
What was your question again?

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:58.200
I'm so excited to talk
about myself.

00:37:58.200 --> 00:38:00.460
AUDIENCE: Just if you're still
doing any of these things.

00:38:00.460 --> 00:38:00.810
JOEL STEIN: Oh, right.

00:38:00.810 --> 00:38:02.700
So I fix some stuff around
my house, but I

00:38:02.700 --> 00:38:03.290
don't have a hobby.

00:38:03.290 --> 00:38:06.440
These guys asked me if I had
hobby, because they just

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:08.590
wanted to connect.

00:38:08.590 --> 00:38:10.430
The amazing thing about, no
matter how different are from

00:38:10.430 --> 00:38:13.870
other people, if you find like
one tiny thing about their

00:38:13.870 --> 00:38:15.980
life that you're interested in,
people are happy to talk

00:38:15.980 --> 00:38:17.240
to you no matter how
different you are.

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:19.240
So the guy just wanted
to bond with me.

00:38:19.240 --> 00:38:20.770
He was like, do you
have any hobbies?

00:38:20.770 --> 00:38:21.840
I was like, I don't.

00:38:21.840 --> 00:38:23.190
He's like, of course
you have a hobby.

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:28.140
He's like I race cars and fix
jet skis, or whatever he did.

00:38:28.140 --> 00:38:30.090
And he had like 10 of them.

00:38:30.090 --> 00:38:32.970
And I was like, how do
people have hobbies?

00:38:32.970 --> 00:38:38.130
I'm either writing, cooking
dinner, or watching my kid.

00:38:38.130 --> 00:38:39.650
Or looking at internet porn.

00:38:39.650 --> 00:38:40.670
Is that a hobby?

00:38:40.670 --> 00:38:42.280
And he said, no, that
wasn't a hobby.

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:43.980
So I'm out.

00:38:43.980 --> 00:38:45.530
I fix stuff around my house.

00:38:45.530 --> 00:38:47.920
And when I say that, I mean like
once every two months I

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:48.400
fix something--

00:38:48.400 --> 00:38:49.860
a small thing.

00:38:49.860 --> 00:38:51.455
So that kind of stuck.

00:38:54.970 --> 00:38:57.340
My interest in cars stuck, but
that's only because my son.

00:38:57.340 --> 00:38:59.090
I've learned a lot more about
cars, gotten more

00:38:59.090 --> 00:38:59.650
interested in them.

00:38:59.650 --> 00:39:02.360
But no, not a lot of it stuck.

00:39:02.360 --> 00:39:04.360
And I don't know why I
don't have hobbies.

00:39:04.360 --> 00:39:06.155
I don't know.

00:39:06.155 --> 00:39:09.450
It just sounds so hard to have
a whole hobby, stuff you do.

00:39:12.180 --> 00:39:13.430
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:39:15.600 --> 00:39:18.800
AUDIENCE: So I was wondering
what other kinds of less

00:39:18.800 --> 00:39:22.250
obvious manly things you might
have looked into, such as--

00:39:22.250 --> 00:39:24.570
obvious things are like doing
the Army training, and riding

00:39:24.570 --> 00:39:26.080
a bull, and whatever.

00:39:26.080 --> 00:39:29.180
But some of the less obvious
things, like maybe the leader

00:39:29.180 --> 00:39:33.340
of a boat crew that goes crab
fishing in Alaska, or doing

00:39:33.340 --> 00:39:35.780
something like raising money
and building a startup

00:39:35.780 --> 00:39:37.970
company, or something
like that.

00:39:37.970 --> 00:39:39.590
Obviously, something near
and dear to us.

00:39:39.590 --> 00:39:41.420
I'm curious about those
experience.

00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:42.540
JOEL STEIN: Yeah.

00:39:42.540 --> 00:39:45.680
So I sold this as a movie
and I was supposed to

00:39:45.680 --> 00:39:46.760
write it and I haven't.

00:39:46.760 --> 00:39:48.040
So I'm now writing it
for another guy.

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:50.410
And we were sitting around
yesterday making a list of

00:39:50.410 --> 00:39:53.610
things that I considered that
we might put in the movie.

00:39:53.610 --> 00:39:57.090
I considered Alaskan king crab
fishing, which is super manly.

00:39:57.090 --> 00:40:00.060
In the end I decided I simply
wanted to have the skills of

00:40:00.060 --> 00:40:04.700
your average American male,
which I defined pretty--

00:40:04.700 --> 00:40:08.980
I think in America we define
masculinity by this very

00:40:08.980 --> 00:40:14.030
Scotch-Irish, Sir Walter
Raleigh, South of the

00:40:14.030 --> 00:40:17.410
Mason-Dixon line, Hatfields
and McCoys, kind of very

00:40:17.410 --> 00:40:20.190
specific masculinity.

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:23.490
I was trying to do what an
average American does that

00:40:23.490 --> 00:40:24.440
fits into that.

00:40:24.440 --> 00:40:26.440
I also did the day trading
thing, which is a very

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:28.360
different Northeastern.

00:40:28.360 --> 00:40:32.520
I was thinking about doing a
British, stiff upper lip,

00:40:32.520 --> 00:40:35.670
drinking tea while the bombs are
falling kind of manliness.

00:40:35.670 --> 00:40:36.960
Didn't really accomplish that.

00:40:36.960 --> 00:40:40.730
So I really stuck to that
Southern American masculinity.

00:40:40.730 --> 00:40:42.860
And all the things I considered
along the lines

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:46.800
that you're talking about,
seemed very extreme and

00:40:46.800 --> 00:40:47.520
different than like--

00:40:47.520 --> 00:40:49.010
I spent a day with the
firefighters in the book,

00:40:49.010 --> 00:40:52.610
which seemed within the realm of
what an average dude might

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:53.780
be able to do.

00:40:53.780 --> 00:40:57.910
Whereas like heli-logging, I
thought about having a coyote

00:40:57.910 --> 00:41:00.140
let me cross the border
from Mexico.

00:41:00.140 --> 00:41:02.250
I thought about doing a
couple days in prison.

00:41:02.250 --> 00:41:05.190
I thought about joining
a biker gang or going

00:41:05.190 --> 00:41:06.090
to Sturgis at least.

00:41:06.090 --> 00:41:09.120
And I thought about
selling crack.

00:41:11.712 --> 00:41:14.650
What else?

00:41:14.650 --> 00:41:16.500
There were a couple things I
didn't do just because people

00:41:16.500 --> 00:41:18.780
didn't call me back.

00:41:18.780 --> 00:41:21.820
Like the Hell's Angels have
a really bad website.

00:41:21.820 --> 00:41:23.750
I don't know if you
guys can fix that.

00:41:23.750 --> 00:41:26.285
They don't respond to their
user questions.

00:41:29.330 --> 00:41:30.930
Some things I got
pretty far with.

00:41:30.930 --> 00:41:34.020
Some things I did and cut from
the book, like I actually

00:41:34.020 --> 00:41:36.760
wound up getting all
the stuff about--

00:41:36.760 --> 00:41:38.980
I spent a day at a
hedge fund I cut.

00:41:38.980 --> 00:41:44.480
I spent three days as a pit crew
in this race that I cut.

00:41:47.440 --> 00:41:50.855
I wanted to spend a couple
weeks, just occasionally at

00:41:50.855 --> 00:41:53.920
night with the Elks, or the
Lions, or any of those groups.

00:41:53.920 --> 00:41:57.360
Just like old dudes talking
about old stories I thought

00:41:57.360 --> 00:41:59.570
would be something very
masculine about that

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:00.860
part of your life.

00:42:00.860 --> 00:42:03.515
It was really an endless amount
of stuff I could do.

00:42:03.515 --> 00:42:05.620
Thought about farming.

00:42:05.620 --> 00:42:08.120
Thought about being a cowboy.

00:42:08.120 --> 00:42:10.310
So yeah, there was really
an endless amount of

00:42:10.310 --> 00:42:11.310
stuff I could do.

00:42:11.310 --> 00:42:13.870
I wish I had done fewer things
actually, and really focused

00:42:13.870 --> 00:42:14.800
more on the depth of it.

00:42:14.800 --> 00:42:17.752
But I'm a lazy writer.

00:42:17.752 --> 00:42:19.002
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:42:22.229 --> 00:42:23.580
JOEL STEIN: You guys
have no work to do.

00:42:26.080 --> 00:42:28.900
AUDIENCE: Of all the different
themes and pieces that you've

00:42:28.900 --> 00:42:32.240
researched and written about,
what made you choose this to

00:42:32.240 --> 00:42:33.790
start writing a book?

00:42:33.790 --> 00:42:36.390
And then, after this whole
experience, do you think

00:42:36.390 --> 00:42:37.640
there's more in the future?

00:42:37.640 --> 00:42:40.810
Are you interested in doing kind
of these more in-depth

00:42:40.810 --> 00:42:42.310
pieces, and stories,
and books?

00:42:42.310 --> 00:42:44.490
And maybe, I guess,
movies later?

00:42:44.490 --> 00:42:45.740
JOEL STEIN: Yeah.

00:42:48.610 --> 00:42:50.660
So after I started at "Time."
part of the reason I took that

00:42:50.660 --> 00:42:53.730
job was so I could
write a book.

00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:55.480
And I had one idea that was
OK that no one wanted

00:42:55.480 --> 00:42:57.340
to buy early on.

00:42:57.340 --> 00:42:59.790
And then, I hadn't really had
an idea I liked enough to

00:42:59.790 --> 00:43:02.160
pursue as a book.

00:43:02.160 --> 00:43:05.210
To be totally frank, I'm not
sure this was that idea.

00:43:05.210 --> 00:43:07.990
It's just that the book industry
was dying and I felt

00:43:07.990 --> 00:43:09.340
like I had to write a book.

00:43:09.340 --> 00:43:11.790
And this was something that I
organically was talking about

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:12.400
and feeling.

00:43:12.400 --> 00:43:15.190
And eventually my friend Josh
was like, you should write a

00:43:15.190 --> 00:43:16.340
book where you learn
to be a man.

00:43:16.340 --> 00:43:18.780
If you're so obsessed with
this, just go do it.

00:43:18.780 --> 00:43:22.410
So it was an opportunity for me
to do a lot of things that

00:43:22.410 --> 00:43:25.640
I wanted to have done, but
wouldn't do unless I had a

00:43:25.640 --> 00:43:29.170
reason because they
all sucked.

00:43:29.170 --> 00:43:30.820
So that's kind of how I decided
to write the book.

00:43:30.820 --> 00:43:32.710
I don't know if that's
the best way to

00:43:32.710 --> 00:43:34.350
decide to write a book.

00:43:34.350 --> 00:43:37.040
If I were to write
another book--

00:43:37.040 --> 00:43:37.810
I don't know.

00:43:37.810 --> 00:43:39.720
I don't know if I would
do it the same way.

00:43:39.720 --> 00:43:41.560
If I did do it the same way,
I know what I would write

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:43.440
about, which is--

00:43:43.440 --> 00:43:45.280
I don't know if I can
describe it quickly.

00:43:45.280 --> 00:43:47.650
But basically, I probably
won't write this book.

00:43:47.650 --> 00:43:49.460
I'll probably have to do a new
genre of book because I think

00:43:49.460 --> 00:43:51.730
the genre of going to do stuff
is getting a little old.

00:43:51.730 --> 00:43:52.820
At least for now.

00:43:52.820 --> 00:43:55.110
But if I were to go do stuff
again, I'm kind of curious

00:43:55.110 --> 00:44:00.580
about the fact that 98% of the
decisions that we make in life

00:44:00.580 --> 00:44:03.520
aren't really our decisions.

00:44:03.520 --> 00:44:05.090
Because it's only practical
to do it this way.

00:44:05.090 --> 00:44:08.430
We do what our society and
our friends are doing.

00:44:08.430 --> 00:44:11.730
So most of the decisions I've
made about how to live my life

00:44:11.730 --> 00:44:14.970
are really demographic and not
the thought-out choices I

00:44:14.970 --> 00:44:15.590
would think.

00:44:15.590 --> 00:44:19.640
So I wanted to go explore both
historically and in present

00:44:19.640 --> 00:44:21.910
time in different cultures how
people live their lives, and

00:44:21.910 --> 00:44:25.370
go do that for a while.

00:44:25.370 --> 00:44:27.040
As simple as living in
a foreign country

00:44:27.040 --> 00:44:28.760
for a couple months.

00:44:28.760 --> 00:44:32.810
Or having my family, my parents
and my wife's parents,

00:44:32.810 --> 00:44:35.800
live with us for a few months
as people do in most of the

00:44:35.800 --> 00:44:36.980
world, always have done.

00:44:36.980 --> 00:44:38.480
Just kind of exploring--

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:40.460
getting super religious for a
little while, just exploring

00:44:40.460 --> 00:44:42.040
different ways to live
and seeing--

00:44:42.040 --> 00:44:44.910
kind of making more thoughtful
choices.

00:44:44.910 --> 00:44:46.015
I realize that didn't
sound funny, but

00:44:46.015 --> 00:44:48.580
it'd be really funny.

00:44:48.580 --> 00:44:51.278
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

